{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "phil-mind-expert",
    "senderColor": "orange",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Yes for Zeroth/First TNs, change Second to \"Constructed Reality\"",
    "content": "\n**Partially yes.** The TNs in footnotes carry less risk than main-text renaming, but the glosses need adjustment.\n\n- Zeroth Reality (TN: \"Ultimate Reality\") -- **Yes, this helps.** The whole point of Zeroth Reality is that it is what traditional metaphysics calls ultimate reality. Telling the reader this in a footnote orients them immediately. And since the author's argument is precisely that Zeroth Reality is inaccessible/constructed, the footnote creates a productive tension: \"this is what tradition calls ultimate reality, but the author will show it is actually generated from First Reality.\" That tension is pedagogically useful.\n\n- First Reality (TN: \"Primary Reality\") -- **Neutral, mildly helpful.** \"Primary\" reinforces the \"first-encountered, foundational\" meaning without much risk. It does not carry the ontological weight of \"Ultimate.\" Harmless and slightly clarifying.\n\n- Second Reality (TN: \"Secondary Reality\") -- **I would change this.** Even in a footnote, \"Secondary\" carries the inferiority connotation. A reader who internalizes \"Secondary Reality\" from the footnote will unconsciously treat constructions-upon-phenomena as lesser. Better TN options: \"Constructed Reality\" (captures the generative relationship -- built from First Reality) or \"Derived Reality\" (captures the structural relationship without the evaluative charge). \"Constructed\" is my preference because it echoes the author's emphasis on construction (构造) throughout the category-theoretic essays.\n\n**Summary:** Yes to Zeroth/Ultimate and First/Primary TNs. Change Second Reality's TN from \"Secondary\" to \"Constructed Reality.\"\n"
  }
}
